MMIGRANT WORKERS AND THEIR FAMILIES IN THE NETHERLANDS.IN THE NETHERLANDS THERE ARE NOW MORE THAN 250,000 IMMIGRANT WORKERS AND THEIRRELATIVES FROM THE POORER MEDITERRANEAN COUNTRIES TOGETHER WITH A FURTHER200,000 FROM THE FORMER DUTCH COLONIES. FOR A NUMBER OF YEARS BRANCH LIBRARIESIN AREAS WITH LARGE NUMBERS OF IMMIGRANT RESIDENTS HAVE PROVIDED MATERIAL INTHE IMMIGRANTS' NATIVE LANGUAGES. AT NATIONAL LEVEL THE NEDERLANDS BIBLIOTHEEKEN LEKTUUR CENTRUM (DUTCH CENTRE FOR LIBRARIES AND LITERATURE) SET UP ACOMMITTEE ON PUBLIC LIBRARY SERVICES FOR IMMIGRANT WORKERS IN JAN 78. THEREPORT OF THE COMMITTEE PUBLISHED IN 1979 RECOMMENDED THE NATIONALCOORDINATION OF THE PROVISION OF LIBRARY MATERIALS FOR IMMIGRANTS AND THEAPPOINTMENT OF A STAFF-MEMBER AT THE NBLC WITH SPECIAL RESPONSIBILITY FORSERVICES TO IMMIGRANTS